The '''Netherlands fallacy''' refers to an error  [[Paul R. Ehrlich]] and his co-authors claim others make in assuming that the [[environmental impact]]s of the [[Netherlands]] and other rich nations are contained within their national borders.

[[Ecologist]]s since the late 20th century have analyzed the ecological sink status and sink capacities of poor nations. As [[Industrial pollution|polluting industries]] migrate from rich to poor nations, the national [[ecological footprint]] of rich nations shrinks, whereas the international ecological footprint may increase or also decrease. The nature of the [[fallacy]] is to ignore increasing environmental damage in many [[developing nations]] and in [[international waters]] attributable to the imported goods or changes in the economy of such nations directly due to [[developed nations]].

Such an approach may lead to incorrect assertions such as the environmental impact of a particular developed country is reducing, when a holistic, international approach suggests the opposite.  This may in turn support over-optimistic predictions toward the improvement of global environmental conditions.{{sfn|Ehrlich|Ehrlich|1990|pp=[https://web.archive.org/web/20060706131457/http://www.2think.org/tpe.shtml 39], 269}}

